postcontent: Beretta Collectors: This Beretta 92S is one of the Second Issue Italian Beretta 92 9mm pistols in beautiful condition. These early pistols still had the magazine release towards the bottom of the left side of the grip frame, and were the first to feature a slide mounted firing pin blocking device. Other features include a beautiful smooth shiny black-anodized lightweight alloy frame, gorgeous deep bluing on the slide (instead of the matte black bruniton finish on the later 92FS and M9 models), a 4.9" barrel, smooth rounded trigger guard, and 15-round magazine. It wears a comfortable set of Pachmayr Signature Model grips.

title: For Sale:  Mossberg Model 185 K-B 20 Gauge Bolt-Action Shotgun
postcontent: This is a Mossberg Model 185 K-B 20 Gauge shotgun. It was a bolt-action based on the reliable Mauser action (Mossberg figured if it worked for rifle in WW1 & 2, it would work for shotguns afterward) and according to Wiki, was produced from 1950-1955. It shoots 2 3/4" shells and has a 2-round magazine that I bought separately online after purchasing the shotgun. It has a muzzle brake and Mossberg's C-Lect-Choke which allows you to change the choke by just twisting the choke near the muzzle.Overall the gun is in great shape for its age, no splits or gashes in the wood stock. The action feels extremely solid and is pretty smooth after I oiled 'er up--trust me, you'll want to fondle this thing all day just smelling the stock and cycling the action. It has a bead front sight. The butt pad has a crack at the toe, this is more of an aesthetic issue if anything as you can't feel it when you shoulder the shotgun. I went to the range to confirm it fires properly, and it does, as anyone would imagine with a bolt gun.Included with the shotgun is the magazine and an Allen soft gun case.

title: For Sale/Trade:  Beretta 1934, pre WWII, .380, Made 1937
location: Fort Thomas, Kentucky near Cincinnati, Northern Kentucky, Kentucky
postcontent: If you can read this listing, the pistol is still for sale; I will deactivate when sold.  I am an 03 FFL, C&R licensee, and will ship, add $20 for normal shipping, more elsewhere if it is non-standard.  A nice pre-WWII, Royal Italian Army, Regia Esercito (RE) stamp in left tang.  Italy introduced this in 1934, hence the Model designation.  Mussolini's Fascist government came to power in later 1922.  Each Beretta from that era is double dated--in this case, the standard "1937" and a Fascist anniversary dating from the 1922 takeover and the Roman Numerals XVI.  Finish is high polish, typical of pre-war guns, and the slide has plummed up--I understand from heat treating. All matching numbers and an original Beretta mag.  FWIW: The Italians also used this pistol for their navy, air force, and other services in 7.65/.32 ACP as the Model 1935.  Shoots fine, bore is in nice condition, etc.  This pistol is a duplicate and it's time to thin the herd a bit.
